library(dplyr)

aggregate(participantsBC$Concmean, 
          by = list(Participant = participantsBC$Participant, 
                    Treatment = participantsBC$Treatment), FUN = mean)

Using a for loop to change treatment levels from 0,1,2,3,4 to very-low, low, moderate, high, very-high respectively on the combined dataset;

changedcombined_df <- combined_df

for(r in 1:nrow(changedcombined_df)) {
  if(changedcombined_df[r,3] == 0) {
    changedcombined_df[r,3] <- "very-low"
  }
  else if(changedcombined_df[r,3] == 1) {
    changedcombined_df[r,3] <- "low"
  }
  else if(changedcombined_df[r,3] == 2) {
    changedcombined_df[r,3] <- "moderate"
  }
  else if(changedcombined_df[r,3] == 3) {
    changedcombined_df[r,3] <- "high"
  }
  else if(changedcombined_df[r,3] == 4) {
    changedcombined_df[r,3] <- "very-high"
  }
}

Writing a function to change treatment levels from 0,1,2,3,4 to very-low, low,moderate, high, very-high respectively, using this with sapply() to change treatment variable in combined dataset;

func_changeddf <- combined_df

labelchanges <- function(n) {
  if(n == 0) {
    return("very-low")
  }
  else if(n == 1) {
    return("low")
  }
  else if(n == 2) {
    return("moderate")
  }
  else if(n == 3) {
    return("high")
  }
  else if(n == 4) {
    return("very-high")
  }
}

func_changeddf$Treatment <- sapply(func_changeddf$Treatment, labelchanges)

How BMI relates to BP for the all study participants;

A correlation test was performed using the procedures indicated below to evaluate the relationship between the two variables (BMI and BP) in order to assess trends. A Pearson correlation test was used to determine the correlation coefficient between two quantitative variables (BMI and BP). The correlation coefficient, which runs from -1 to 1, is a symmetric measure of relationship between two variables. The covariance method and the cor.test() method were used to compute the correlation coefficient. The covariance expresses how much BMI and BP change together and whether their relationship is positive or negative. The correlation allows us to further analyze the covariance by identifying both the direction and degree of the link. Cor.test() for Pearson correlation is used for quantitative continuous variables with a linear relationship and returns the Pearsons product-moment correlation coefficient.

library(ggplot2)

#calcuating correlation coefficient using covariance
cov(statsFile$BMI, statsFile$BP)
## [1] 0.01065146
cov(statsFile$BMI, statsFile$BP)/(sd(statsFile$BMI)*sd(statsFile$BP))
## [1] 0.9997509
#OR directly using correlation test
cor.test(statsFile$BMI, statsFile$BP)
## 
##  Pearson's product-moment correlation
## 
## data:  statsFile$BMI and statsFile$BP
## t = 798.75, df = 318, p-value < 2.2e-16
## alternative hypothesis: true correlation is not equal to 0
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  0.9996895 0.9998001
## sample estimates:
##       cor 
## 0.9997509
#plot for visualization of the relationship
ggplot(statsFile, mapping = aes(x = BMI, y = BP)) + 
  geom_point() + geom_smooth(method = 'lm', formula = y ~ x) + 
  theme_bw() + labs(title = "Relationship between BMI and BP", x = "BMI", y = "BP")

Results Interpretation

Covariance and Correlation : Because the nature of the relationship between BMI and BP is positive (a positive covariance value), when BMI rises, so does BP. BMI and blood pressure showed a strong positive linear association, according to the correlation coefficient of 0.9997509. Subsequently the significant covariance and correlation showed that BMI and BP have a strong positive linear association. The correlation coefficient was almost exactly one, showing a nearly perfect positive linear relationship.

Correlation test : The Pearsons product-moment correlation result yielded a p value less than 0.05, indicating statistical significance and allowing the null hypothesis of true correlation equals 0 to be rejected. The correlation coefficient had a 95% confidence interval of 0.9996895 to 0.9998001. It lacked the null value, indicating statistical significance and so null hypothesis rejection. In conclusion, the correlation test confirmed the substantial positive linear association between BMI and BP.

Scatter plot : As a best practice, this relationship was also depicted using a scatter plot.The scatter plot depicted the association between BMI and BP. Visualization with a scatter plot also assisted us in determining whether we had any outliers that could significantly skew the correlation coefficient. The outliers observed here didnt drastically change our correlation but they should be further investigated. The geom_smooth() function added a linear regression line to the plot, indicating the strength and direction of the link.

Furthermore, to compare the two samples, we used a measure of central tendency computed for each sample (in this case, the mean). A Students t-test for unpaired samples was used to assess whether the means of two independent samples are significantly different. An F test was used to compare the variances of BMI and BP, as shown below.

#Comparison of the means
meanBMI_BP <- sapply(statsFile[2:3], mean)
meanBMI_BP
##      BMI       BP 
## 3.185907 1.814074
mean_comparison <- t.test(statsFile$BMI, statsFile$BP) #student's t-test to compare means
mean_comparison
## 
##  Welch Two Sample t-test
## 
## data:  statsFile$BMI and statsFile$BP
## t = 121.36, df = 369.13, p-value < 2.2e-16
## alternative hypothesis: true difference in means is not equal to 0
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  1.349605 1.394060
## sample estimates:
## mean of x mean of y 
##  3.185907  1.814074
#Comparison of the variances
varianceBMI_BP <- sapply(statsFile[2:3], var)
varianceBMI_BP
##         BMI          BP 
## 0.037890841 0.002995712
variance_comparison <- var.test(statsFile$BMI, statsFile$BP) #F test to compare two variances
variance_comparison
## 
##  F test to compare two variances
## 
## data:  statsFile$BMI and statsFile$BP
## F = 12.648, num df = 319, denom df = 319, p-value < 2.2e-16
## alternative hypothesis: true ratio of variances is not equal to 1
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  10.15190 15.75872
## sample estimates:
## ratio of variances 
##           12.64836

Results Interpretation

Student t-test results : To understand the preceding findings, we first determined the individual means of the variables BMI and BP. The Students t-test was performed on the assumption that these are independent variables and that there is no difference between the means of BMI and BP, i.e.the true difference in means is equal to 0 as our null hypothesis. Because the p value is 2.2e-16, we reject the null hypothesis of equal means at the 5% level of significance. The results provided adequate evidence to reject the hypothesis that there is no difference between the means of BMI and BP. The null value was not contained in the 95% confidence range, indicating statistical significance. Moreover, the t-value of 121.36 represents the difference in standard deviations between the means of the two groups. A bigger absolute t-value implied that the difference between the groups is more significant. Ultimately, the BMI and BP means diverge, and this difference is statistically significant.

F-test results : For the comparison of the two variances, our null hypothesis was that the true ratio of variances is equal to one. Based on this assumption, the F test revealed that the ratio of variances obtained was 12.64836, which is clearly not equal to one. Nonetheless, the p-value was less than 0.05, indicating statistical significance and thus rejection of the null hypothesis, and this also verifies the results obtained by computing the individual variances of BMI and BP. Subsequently the F test indicates a substantial difference in variances between BMI and BP. The p-value obtained was quite low, indicating that the null hypothesis of equal variances could be rejected. The ratio of variances confidence interval didnt include 1, further supporting the conclusion that the variances were significantly different.

How disease status (phenotype) is related to gender;

A statistical test appropriate for categorical or qualitative variables was employed to investigate the relation between disease and gender. This is referred to as the Chi-square test of independence. The Chi-square test of independence compares observed frequencies (those in your sample) to expected frequencies if there is no association between the two categorical variables (those expected if the null hypothesis is true). The null hypothesis for the Chi-square test of independence is that no association exists between the two categorical variables (Disease Status and Gender), implying that these variables are independent. The alternative hypothesis is that there is a link, and hence the variables are dependent on one another.

##creation of contingency tables

  labs(title = "A barplot of Status by Gender", x = "Status", y = "Gender" )

chisq.test(contigency_table)
## 
##  Pearson's Chi-squared test with Yates' continuity correction
## 
## data:  contigency_table
## X-squared = 0.86632, df = 1, p-value = 0.352

Results Interpretation

To analyze these results, first a contingency table was created that showed the observed number of individuals with the disease or not; based on their gender. This could also be represented with a bar graph of the disease status filled by Gender(Male or Female). The p value from the Pearsons Chi-squared test was 0.352, so at the 5% significance level, we failed to reject the null hypothesis, indicating that there was no significant relationship between disease status and gender and that there is insufficient evidence to suggest that gender and disease status are associated. As a result, this was consistent with the premise that disease condition and gender are unrelated.

Constructing an appropriate model to show the relationship between BMI and BP;

We used regression analysis to build a model that demonstrated the link between BMI and BP. Specifically, a simple linear regression model to describe the effect of a specific variable on the value of a continuous outcome variable, known as the response variable. We wanted to model a quantitative response variable (BP) as a function of a predictor variable (BMI) in this scenario.

fit.model <- lm(BP ~ BMI, data = statsFile)

Results Interpretation

The mean and median were determined to describe the centrality of the numeric observations of BMI per different sampling locations (A, B, and C). The typical BMI values for locations A, B, and C ranged from 3.17 to 3.21. The medians were also close together, ranging from 3.17 to 3.21. These results provided a snapshot of the datas normal distribution. Remember that the mean and median of normally distributed data are equal. The standard deviations obtained were relatively small, showing that BMI levels are relatively consistent within each sampling location.

The variance of BMI for the different locations were remarkably similar; confirming the assumption of equal variances in order to perform a one-way ANOVA test. The closeness in these variances was also highlighted further by visualization. Furthermore, the summary of the entire dataset shows a range of BMI values from 2.606 to 3.830.

Visualization: The boxplot is an excellent tool for visualizing the distribution of a BMI over various sampling locations. Two outliers were found, one at Location A and one at Location B. These outliers should ideally be investigated, but in this situation, ANOVA is more robust and will not be influenced by outliers. It could also be seen that the box and whiskers are comparable across all sites. The scatter plot showed that the points for all of the different sites were nearly identical, indicating that the variance is quite comparable. The histogram indicated that the normalcy assumption appeared to be met. Moreover, the histogram resembled a bell curve, indicating that the data should be normally distributed.

One-way ANOVA : Based on the assumptions, the aov() function was used to test the null hypothesis that there is no significant difference in the mean BMI values among the three sampling locations. In other words, the average BMI is the same across all sampling locations. The p-value reported was 0.28, indicating that there is no statistical significance and hence we cannot reject the null hypothesis. This suggested that the location effect was not statistically significant and also very tiny (F = 1.278). In conclusion, theres insufficient evidence to conclude that theres a substantial variation in mean BMI values among the three sampling locations based on the data.

How disease status depends on both BMI and BP;

A useful statistical modeling approach for more than two variables was employed to understand how illness status can be influenced by both BMI and BP. Because disease status is the qualitative dependent variable in this situation, and an individual either has or does not have the disease, a binary logistic regression model was built for this investigation. Logistic regression is appropriate for binary outcomes like illness status (yes/no).

dependency <- glm(Status ~ BMI + BP, 
                  data = statsFile, family = binomial)
summary(dependency)
## 
## Call:
## glm(formula = Status ~ BMI + BP, family = binomial, data = statsFile)
## 
## Coefficients:

## BP             13.67      92.02   0.149    0.882

## Residual deviance: 442.99  on 317  degrees of freedom
## AIC: 448.99
## 
## Number of Fisher Scoring iterations: 3

Results Interpretation

From the code above, the dependent variable was Status (disease status), and the independent variables were BMI and BP. The family = binomial argument specified the logistic regression model. The summary() provided more detailed information about coefficients, p-values and so on. Looking at the coefficients;

Intercept : this represents the estimated log-odds of the baseline category (e.g., disease status = 0) when both BMI and BP are zero. The intercept in this case was not statistically significant (p-value = 0.890), and the estimate was -11.64.

BMI : The coefficient for BMI obtained was -4.15. It thus indicated the change in the log-odds of the disease for a one-unit increase in BMI while holding BP constant. However, the coefficient was not statistically significant (p-value = 0.873), suggesting that BMI is not a significant predictor of disease status in this model.

BP : The coefficient for BP was 13.67. It represented the change in the log-odds of the disease for a one-unit increase in BP while holding BMI constant. Similar to BMI, the coefficient for BP was not statistically significant (p-value = 0.882), indicating that BP is not a significant predictor of disease status in this model.

Number of Fisher Scoring Iterations is 3 indicating three iterations the algorithm went through to estimate the coefficients.

In conclusion, based on the p-values, BMI and BP appeared to be statistically non-significant predictors of disease status in this logistic regression model. It is therefore suggested that there was no evidence of a relationship between BMI, BP, and disease status.
